    "created_at": "2015-03-26T22:49:32Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-03-26T23:07:19Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I think the \"bug\" that was referenced before is the following:\n\n![output](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/599274/6858628/1fd543e6-d3d6-11e4-9862-0043d2267902.gif)\n\nEvery time the page jumps is because I was pressing tab to focus distinct elements of the page. Another example in LibreOffice similar to what we have (using tab and changing the font size):\n\n![output2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/599274/6858669/7a9d2230-d3d6-11e4-8556-51847779db86.gif)\n\nI don't think this is a bug. If you scroll down and leave your focus behind and then perform an action, the page will jump to show you the place in which the change took place. Otherwise, it would be confusing. The alternative would be to change focus as you scroll down, but that is not the standard behavior at all and would require a lot of events to keep track of the `innerWidth` and `innerHeight` of the `window` object. \n\nI think the only way to achieve this is replacing the cursor and use a `div` instead. That way, you have full control of the focus behavior. This is what Google Docs did when they rewrote the application from scratch. Keep in mind that they are using a `span` for each line in the document. However, Google Docs also jumps when you change something. It doesn't jump when a state changes (such as font-size), though.\n"
  },
